    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter May 4th with a clear emphasis on exploiting high-ceiling matchups against volatile arms. The standout play of the day is **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (82.13), whose elite speed profile is perfectly amplified by a soft matchup against Chase Petty (xERA 6.57). While his #8 spot in the lineup typically dampens expectations, the confluence of a favorable park, wind conditions, and a weak opposing SP creates a rare opportunity for stolen bases and counting stats. Similarly, **Trea Turner** (65.20) and **Yordan Alvarez** (63.86) remain mandatory starts; **Trea Turner** leverages his lead-off role to capitalize on a moderate matchup against Janson Junk, while **Yordan Alvarez** remains a locked-in asset despite the inherent difficulty of facing Yoshinobu Yamamoto, largely due to his elite xwOBA metrics.\n\nWe are keeping a close watch on **Carson Benge** (63.27), who grades out as a strong start against Tomoyuki Sugano; however, a 34% rain risk necessitates a secondary plan should the game face significant delays. Regarding the bench, **Caleb Durbin** (40.27) was the last man cut from the active lineup. While **Caleb Durbin** offers high-end stolen base potential, the optimizer flagged his matchup against Tarik Skubal\u2014one of the league\u2019s most efficient arms\u2014as a prohibitive risk. Skubal\u2019s ability to limit base runners and suppress production outweighed the stolen base upside that **Caleb Durbin** provides, leading to the decision to preserve game caps instead.\n\nStrategic deployment of the platoon advantage also heavily influenced today's configuration. **Dillon Dingler** (54.51) and **Luke Raley** (54.46) both saw their scores buoyed by positive platoon splits, effectively pushing them into our lineup over lower-upside alternatives. While **Hyeseong Kim** (41.69) sits near our floor for acceptable starts, his inclusion is a calculated gamble on his ability to exploit the slow delivery of Steven Okert to manufacture a stolen base\u2014a category where our obsession with speed remains the primary driver of roster construction.",
